==Chinese==

===Glyph origin===
{{Han etyl}}
{{Han compound|門|一|廾|t1=door|t2=latch and/or wooden pole that shuts a door|t3=a pair of hands|ls=ic}} — a pair of hands opening a latched door. {{zh-l|*一}} and {{zh-l|*廾}} are combined into {{zh-l|*开}} since the Small Seal script; however, in the conservative variant [[𨵑]], the two hands and the latch are well visible.

Compare {{zh-l|*闢}}. See also {{zh-l|*關}}, in which the door is kept shut by two wooden poles.

===Etymology 1===
{{zh-forms|s=开|alt=𫔭-obsolete Singapore simplified,䦐,𨴉,𨳩,𨴂,𨵹,𨶘,𨵑}}
According to STEDT, from {{inh|zh|sit-pro|*m/s-k(w)a-j||mouth; opening; spread; door; face; jaw}}. Cognate with {{och-l|戶|door}}, {{cog|bo|ཁ||mouth}}, {{cog|bo|སྒོ||door}}.

The word is possibly a colloquial variant of {{och-l|闓}} ({{zh-ref|Schuessler, 2007}}). {{cog|hmx-mie-pro|*kʰu̯ɔiᴬ||to open}} (whence {{cog|ium|kʰɔi¹}}) and {{cog|th|ไข}} are Chinese loans ({{zh-ref|Ratliff, 2010}}).

